home on the pig's back
Homonym Number:
Word Class: phrase
Sense Number:
Definition:successful, victorious (cf. home and dry/hosed etc.)
Origin: [none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See: also pig's back, on the
Pronunciation:
Notes: [W Ramson: NSW rural sport of riding pigs]
Citations
Date:  0/0/1937
Source:  Dictionary of Slang
Author:  PARTRiDGE
Vol / Page:  400
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Home on the pig's back</i>. Very successful!; thoroughly (and easily): a c.p., mostly among New Zealanders and Australians: from ca. 1910. Cf. (?) <i>save one's bacon. </i>
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1943
Source:  Pure Gold
Author:  HiSLOP
Vol / Page:  34
Edition:
Quote:  Sir Swithen [a horse] was not home and dried, nor was he home on the pig's back, as some would also say of an easy win.
